        <h1>Quality Checks Workflow</h1>
        <p>The typical <MadCap:variable name="General.Liquibase" /> quality checks workflow looks as follows:</p>
        <p>DBAs, Architects, Developers and others in your organization may have set specific standards for database changes and security roles. <MadCap:variable name="General.Liquibase" /> quality checks can be configured (copied, customized, enabled, disabled) on the command line to meet these standards, which are stored in an auto-generated configuration file called <code>liquibase-checks-settings.conf</code>. Your organization's teams can have multiple configuration files.</p>
        <p>Next, a team obtains configuration files for a specific project from source code control. It is best practice to keep the checks configuration with the <MadCap:variable name="General.changelog" /> in source code control so that it is delivered to anyone who works with the <MadCap:variable name="General.changelog" />.</p>
        <p>Then, from the command line, you can navigate to the location of the <MadCap:variable name="General.Liquibase" /><MadCap:variable name="General.changelog" /> and configuration files and run <code>checks</code> subcommands to configure and execute checks. For more information, see .</p>
        <p>Changes, such as new copies, customizations, enabled status, and disabled status, are saved in the checks settings file, which you can commit to source control to be used in development, on-demand, and automated quality checks executions.</p>
